Here’s a basic implementation using a simple polynomial function. We'll use a class to represent polynomials and a method to compute their derivatives. This won't handle complex functions or non-polynomial expressions, but it should be a good starting point.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

class Polynomial {
public:
    std::vector<int> coefficients;

    Polynomial() : coefficients({0}) {}

    // Constructor to initialize with specific coefficients
    Polynomial(std::vector<int> coeffs) : coefficients(coeffs) {}

    // Method to print the polynomial
    void print() const {
        for (size_t i = 0; i < coefficients.size(); ++i) {
            if (coefficients[i] != 0) {
                std::cout << coefficients[i];
                if (i > 0) std::cout << "x^" << i;
                if (i < coefficients.size() - 1) std::cout << " + ";
            }
        }
        std::cout << std::endl;
    }

    // Method to compute the derivative
    Polynomial derivative() const {
        Polynomial der;
        for (size_t i = 1; i < coefficients.size(); ++i) {
            der.coefficients.push_back(i * coefficients[i]);
        }
        return der;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Example usage
    Polynomial p({3, 2, 1}); // Represents 3x^2 + 2x + 1
    std::cout << "Original polynomial: ";
    p.print();

    Polynomial dp = p.derivative();
    std::cout << "Derivative: ";
    dp.print();

    return 0;
}
```

This code is pretty straightforward and efficient for polynomials. It uses a vector to store the coefficients of the polynomial, which is both time and space efficient. The `derivative` method computes the derivative by simply multiplying each coefficient by its corresponding power and then decrementing the power by one.

